{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_kestrel_ver01/data/sn85060004/00516994733/1937091001/0297.xml":{"full_text":"10-B\nHANEY GEEKS\n3T 0CK BREAK\nANSWER\nBy LEWIS HANEY\nProfessor of Economics, New\nYork University.\nCopyright By The Light.\nNEW YORK, Sept. 10.\u2014Probably\nome of the most frequent questions\nnpw asked is, what does the break\nin the stock market mean? Is\nthere something back of it that\ndoes not appear to the eve?\nAt least, this is the big question\nthat confronts me as I settle down\nat my desk after a quiet month up\nfn the New Hampshire hills.\n-I have talked with several keen\nand well-posted men about the mat\nter, and tried to think things\nthrough myself, The general diag\nnosis I reach is about as follows:\nThere are five factors to con\nsider: (1) The war scare; (2) the\ntechnical condition of the market.\nnotably its thinness, (3) the condi\ntion of sentiment and business phy\nchology, (4) the outlook for business,\nand (5) the political outlook. All\nof these have played their part in\ncausing the break.\n\u201cTo begin with, the market was\nshaky and very, very thin. In fact,\nthe big decline Tuesday amply certi-\nfies the prediction of the critics of\ngovernment regulation who forecast\nthese wild gyrations as a result of\nreduced liquidity.\nI think that we can now be sure\nthat the July rally brought techni\ncal weakness into the market. It\nwas overbought,\nThis condition was made worse by\nthe so-called loop-hole tax which\ngreatly reduces the chance of the\nvery wealthy large-scale investor to\nmake any money by buying and\nholding stocks. i\nI think that many persons figur-\ned that a fall rally was certain.\nMany others are influenced by low\ninterest rates to keep their money\nin stocks. Then as the July raily\npetered out and the market sagged,\nthese people held on, saying that\nthey were taking an \u201cinvestment\nposition.\u201d\nBut as weeks went by, and the\nsagging continued. they became jit-\ntery. They learned that some \u201cin\nsiders\u201d had liquidated in July. They\nfound doubts arising about fall\nbusiness, and their hopes of a fall\nrally in the market dimmed. Then\nthey forgot about \u201cinvesting,\u2122 and1\nbecame mere speculators eager to\nget out with a trading profit or to\u2018l\navoid a trading loss.\nFinally, this shaky, jittery, lh'ml\nmarket was hit by several disturb-\ning forces. First came the new\ndoubts about business, suggested by\nthe letdown in building and in steel\nproduction, and by the weakening\nof government credit shown by the\nrediscount rate cut and higher\nrates paid on government notes.\nThen the war scare pushed it over.\nIt was a real war scare this time.\nGrain prices soared. European ex-\nchanges were weak.\nAll sources agree that there was\nsome European selling of our stocks\non balance. (It seems fairly clear,\nhowever, that the volume of such\nselling was not large, judged by\nformer standards. Certainly little\nif any of the proceeds of such sales\nhave been taken out of this coun\ntry). i\nSe we had such a severe crack\nthat a technical rally is practically\ncertain. This is the more certain,\nbecause of the two main factors in\nthe decline are temporary: (1)\nTechnical weakness is automatical-\nly cured by \u201cclimax selling;\u201d (2)\nand the war scare, though more se-\nripus than predecessors is probably\nJust another scare. (These dictators\nseem a bit jumpy, but T notice thati\nthey have so much trouble at home\nthat they don\u2019t attack any first\nclass powers.)\nI agree with the numerous ob-\nservers who do not expect any Fu-\nropean war or any war between the\nUnited States and Japan.\n\u2014_\nAccordingly, the course of the\nmarket after the next rally, de-|\npends upon the business outlcok.\nThe prospect for fall business is\nnot entirely clear, but I am inclin-\ned to think that those who were too\nbullish in July are too bearish now.\nAfter all, the farmers do have large\ncrops, and the present administra\u2014\u2018\ntion does have huge monetary re-\nserves for spending.\n\u2018Is it a new idea that we will be\nforced to resort to more inflation?\n\nPeace prevailed alone San An\ntorio\u2019s labor front Friday as sched-\nuled violence failed to materialize at\ntwo sites of picketing by the Hod\nCarriers, Building and Common La-\nborers union.\nApproximately 20 men were added\nte the group building a $200.000\nnurses\u2019 home at Santa Rosa hos-\npital as eight pickets patrolled the\nsidewalks with strike placards. Po-\nlice had been warned that violence\nwould result if additional men were\nemploved by H. H. Moeller, con\u2014]\ntractor.\nT. P. Lucas, foreman, insisted that\nthere was no strike, He said he was\npaying both union and non-union\nmen 35 cents an hour.\nAt the Southern Transfer com-\npany. Medina and San Luis streets,\npickets continued their peaceful pa\ntrelling in attempt to gain higher\nwages and union recognition.\nCommissioner Phil Wright has\nennounced that peaceful picketingl\nwould be allowed at both sifes.\nFRIDAY.\nDespite this year's prospects for\nthe highest farm income since 1929,\nthere has been only a small de\ncrease in the amount of outstanding\nagricultural loans made by federal\ncredit agencies since 1936, this chart\nshows,\nThe U. S. bureau of agricultural\neconomics estimates that American\nfarmers will receive nine billion\nOPPOaE VETS\nUFFIGE MOVE\nAssistance of Texas congressmen\nto halt moving of the regional of\ni fices of the veterans administration\nfrom San Antonlo to Waco was be\nling sought Friday by Congressman\nMaury Maverick.\nMaj. Gen. Frank T. Hines, admin\nistrator of the veterans administra\ntion, recently informed Maverick\nthat it had been decided to remove\nthe regional offices to Waco, main\ntaining a skeleton staff here. The\nDallas regional office will also be\nshifted to Waco, under the plan.\nMaverick said that Hines had\npremised him no action would be\ntaken until Texas senators and rep\nresentatives had been consulted.\nThe San Antonio solon said he\nhad written to other Texas con\ngressmen Thursday soliciting their\nsupport in the fight to prevent any\nchange in regional offices.\nY\nGrain Market\nCHICAGO, Sept, 10\u2014 (AP)\u2014Maore\nthan a cent a bushel setback to Chi\ncago wheat values today accompanied\nby persistent reports of bz export\nCcompetition on the part of Russia,\nCoupled with word thut 45 steamers\nCfor the past few dayvs had been chao-\nCtered fop grain shipments; frone South\nCRussian ports were indications ol al-\nCmozst complete absence of a broader\nCdemund overseas for wheat from the\n\u2019Ullill\u2018ll States. In the face of such cir-\nCcumstances, the trade gave little heed\ntoassertions that recent rains were\nthreatening extensive damage to a con\nsiderable portion of Russian crops, es\npecially those where sheaf grain is\nstanding in the ficlds unthreshed, Act\ning also as a weight on values were\ndispatches from Washington suggesting\nlikelihood that United States neutral\nity regulations may include wheat as\na prohibited article of export to belig\nerents in the Orient.\nPrivate advices in some quarters\nsaid_quite a bit of wheat had been sold\nby Russia overnizht to Great Britain\nand to European continental countries\nas well. One version was that British\npurchasing of wheat from Russia to\ntaled 24,000 tons, Meanwhile, the Liv\nerpool wieat market, due 's to fs oof\na cent lower, closed today 75 to 1\ncent down,\nCorn, oats and rve svmpathized with\nwheat market downturns. Ryve and corn\neach tumbled in some cases more than\n2 cents a hushel,\nDespite higher quotations on hozs,\nprovisions responded to grain price set\nbacks, 1\n\nSAN ANTONIO GRAIN.\nFarmers received the following prices\non the Sun Antonio grain market\nFriday:\nCorn: White, 80\u00a2 to S85\u00a2 a bushel.\nCorn: White, on ear, 55\u00a2 to 70\u00a2 bu.\nCorn: Mixed yellow and white, 7S\u00a2\nto 80c a bushel.\nCorn: Yellow, on ear, 55\u00a2 to 7hc a\nbushel.\nCorn: Yellow, 80\u00a2 tn S5\u00a2 a hushel,\nMilo maize: $1 to $1.20 cwt.\nKaffir: 9% to $1.20 cwt,\nWheat: Ilard, $1.03 a bushel.\nWheat: Soft. \u00a71 a bushel,\nOats: 35\u00a2 a bushel,\nj SAN ANTONIO HAY.\nFarmers recelved the following prices\nfor hay on the San Antonio market\nFriday:\nNo. 1 Johnson grass, $8 ton.\nNo. 2 Johnson grass, $7 ton.\nSouth Texas prairie hay, $11.40 fon.\nLocal prairvie hay. $8.50 {on.\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\n\u2018('uu',\\(;o GRAIN AND PROVISIONS\nCHICAGO, Sept, 10\u2014 (AP)\u2014Quota\ntions\nOpen Close Close\nWheat-\u2014 Todav Yesterday Yr. Azo\nSeptember S1LOT':z \u00a71.0755 $1.123;\nDecember 1.09 1.095\u00a2 112\nMay 1.11% 1117 1,103\nCorn-\u2014\u2014\nSeptember 1.0515 1.061% 11255\nOctober B0y L\nDecember\u2019 1D lan anil)\nMav .65 6514 0005\nOats\u2014\nCSeptember L, 21 Alg AR\nDecember 203 307 L4214\nMav .12 317 A3\nSov beans\nCOctoher .0 003 100\nDecember 08 R ceee\nCMavooo 80 100\nRye\nSeptemher, KOy LR234 Sg\nDecember TS 50 K17\nCMay TR R0y L0\nNo harley--\nLard\u2014\nSeptembep 1045 1175\nOctober .10.50 10,52 11,80\nDecember .10.45 1057 1102\n\\Janunn\u2019 L..1047 10,60 e\nBellies\u2014\nSentember 15.87 1335\nOctober 15.70 S\nDollar Market\nLONDON, Sept. 10.\u2014(AP)\u2014With\nofficial control lacking, French francs\nslumped under heavy continental sell\ning in the foreign exchange market to\nday. Final quotation was 139 to the\npound against 134,37 yvesterday. The\nunit made some recovery in late deal\ningsf rom the day's low of 140.37,\nThe United States dollar gained 13\nof a cent, ending $4.94'% to the pound\ncompared with a New York \u2018overnight\nsterling rate of $4.94%.\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014\nPARIS, Sept. 10.\u2014(AP)\u2014The United\nStates dollar clozed 2815 franecs (3,552\neentz to the franc) in foreign exchange\ndealings todav. This compares with\nIpr York's overnight franc rate of\n3.632 cents,\nWANT ADS\u2014FANNIN 1231\nFarm Income\ndollars for their 1937 crop market-\nIings and \u201cbeneflit\u201d payments by the\ngovernment. Farm loans by gov\n}ernment agencies averaged an out\n\u2018standing amount of $3,638.000,000\n(in the first six months of 1937, com\n'pared with average outstanding\nloans of $3.644.000,000 in the full\nvear 1936, about double the 1929\namount.\n36,000 NOW IN\ng, N, SCHODLS\nEnrollment in the San Antonio\ncity schools was expected to reach\nthie 36,000 mark by Friday night, ac\ncording to James T. Shea, new cen\n\u2018sus and attendance director for the\nbeard of education.\nA total of 25193 students had\nregistered at the close of school\nThursday afternoon.\nThe registration rush will con\ntinue for a few more days and then\nslump until the middle of October,\n'when the return of San Antonio\nI families from the cotton fields will\nS cause a new rise, Shea said.\nPeak attendance last year was ap\nproximately 43,000. and this is ex\npected to be exceeded when the cot\nten pickers place their children in\nschool, he added.\nThe city\u2019s new vocational and\nagricultural school, the Luther Bur\nbenk, reported an attendance of 484\nstudents, drawn principally from the\nLanier, Page and Brackenridge\nscizools, Shea declared,\nOf the 1200 new studehts sent\nLome because they lacked vaccina\ntion certificates, all but 300 were\nback in class Friday, having been\nvaccinated,\nCotton Market\nNEW ORLEANS, Sepl. 10 (AP)\nCotton futures opened steady, net 4\nto 6 points lower on execution of some\novernight selling orders and liquida\ntion by recent buyers,\nThe selling was not aggressive but\n\u2019dnm:md was lackine and the continued\nuncertainty abroad discouraged new ac\ntivity,\nOctaber opened at 9.10\u00a2, Decemhber\nCat 9.15\u00a2. January 9.19\u00a2, March 9.27\u00a2,\nMay 9.36c and July 9.46\u00a2,\nTrading was quiet after the start\n\u2018nml prices eased a point or two addi\ntional on a few sales,\nToward the end of the first half houy\nCactive positions were 6 to 9 points net\nlower.\nLiverpool eables were not up to ex-\nCpectations and aided the easiness in\nCearly dealings\nDomestic goods markets continued\nquiet but prices held steady, private\nCreports indicated,\ne\ns O ere\u2014\nNEW YORK FUTURES.\nBATTNERY TPt Tr e e TN e a\nNEW YORK. Sept. 10.\u2014(AP)\u2014Cot\nton futures opened steady\nPrev.Close, Open.\nOctober 007 912\nDecember oL 13 9.00\n\u2019Janu:u,\\' 017 9.1\nMarch ..o, 7.27 0,22\n[Mav ....ooool 906 \ufb02.fll\u2018\n[duly oo 0.46 9.40\n1\nNEW ORLEANS FUTVRES,\nNEW ORLEANS, Sept, 10\u2014 (ADP)\nCotton futures opened steady,\nPrec.Close, Open.\nOctober oo 0.14 210\nDecember 920 915\nJanuary 220 910\nMareh ....o.oooaa,.. 0082 0.27\nMay oo 0.42 9.86\nJuly ool o0 000 9.46\nL\ne\nviverroorn corrox\nLIVERPOOL, Sept. 10\u2014 (AP)\u2014Cot\nton, 6000 bales including 300 Ameri\ncan. Good business in spot. prices 1\npoint higher. Quotations in pence:\nAmerican striet good middling 631\nwood middling 6 01; strict middling\n5761 middling 546 strict low middling\n5.21: low middling 471 striet good\nordinary 4.21: good ordinary 3 81, Fu.\ntures cloged steady. October 5.27: De.\ncember 5300 January 3,33, March 5,38\nMay 5.43; July 548\nR\nTIVERPOOJ, SPOT WHEAT\nLIVERPOOL. Sent. 10\u2014 (AT) \u2014Spot\nwheat, No. 1 Manitoba, 10s 9d: new\nrosafe 95 4d; Indian-Karachi 95 1d:\n~Australian 9s 3d,\ne\nLIVERPOOL, WHEAT\nLIVERPOOL, Sept. 10 (AP)\nWheat futures closed quiet: October\n1.2014: December 1,295 March 1,24\nexchange \u00a74,94,\nY\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014\nNAVAL STORES\nARIR TSRS s34 NOELEAEY\nSAVANNAIH, Sept. 10\u2014 (AP)\u2014Tur\npentine firm 301 e: sales 164 receipts\n612: shipments 10: stocks 38,333,\nRosin firm, sales 618: yeceipts 1525,\nshinments none: stock 59 608,\nouote: ROD, and B 7500 FG\nand M., 7.80c. T 7.85c: K. \u00ab7.90c: M.\n702000 N, \u00a300c; WG, \u00a3.20c; WW and\n\u2018x' 8.65\u00a2.\n\nCity News\nDance Sat. night. Sept. 11, Helotes\nHerman Sons hall, on Brown Rd.\nMusic by Slick Jones.\u2014(Adv.)\nO\nDance K. T. Sat, Sept. 11. Cor\nrinne orch. Gents 40c. ladies 10c.\n8 to 12.\u2014(Adv.)\n\nLee Kohlenberg playing Sat. night\non the open air roof, Tourist club,\n617 N. St. Mary's. Adm. 35\u00a2c.\u2014(Adv.)\n\nLeon Springs Lodge, nicest, most\nprivate and inexpensive place to go\nfor amusement. Open day and night.\n\u2014(Adv.)\n\nDance at Macdona Sat, nite, T.i1-\nlie and Johnnie's Orch.\u2014(Ady.)\nTHE SAN ANTONIO LIGHT.\nRAIL CONTROL\nAL\nR\nBy MERRYLE S. RUKEYSER\nCopvright By The Lirht.\ncopyrignt By ne Lignt\nNEW YORK, Sept, 10.\u2014L. W.\nBaldwin, able chief operating ex\n(,ecutive of the Misosuri Pacific lines,\ni tocay, in a statement to this writer,\nmade a plea to business men gen\nrerally to halt the drift toward gov\nerment ownership of the railroads.\niBaldwin said:\nI \u201cIf the railroads should be plung\ned into governmiental ownership I\nam certain that business and public\n\u2018semiment would develop a strong,\n'a(:tive and nationwide movement tq\n\u2019r(-store them to private ownership.\n\"Isn\u2019t it possible for some such\nfx:lo\\\u2019vmcnt 1o be organized now to\nprevent the carriers from being\nforced imto such a low financial\nsiate, through increasing burplens.\u2019\nthat there will be no alternative to\n\u2018a federally owned gnd operated|\ntransportation system?\"\nReferring to the new railroad\ncrisis, Baldwin declared l\n\u201cNever in the many years I have\nbeen engaged in railroading has\nthere been a greater need for the\u2019\npublic to have a full and complete\nrealization of the conditions against\ni which the railroads are being forced\nto struggle. And unless opinion is\n\u2019cr,\\'st.allized in some manner that\nwill put an end to everlasting sad-\nI dling of the carriers with additional\n;.bm'dens, 1. for one, do not see how\ntlie public can hope to enjoy indefi\nnitely the benefits of an efficlent.\u2018\ndependable, and low cost transpor-\ntation system.\n*For a great many years the rail- l\nroads have been meeting the triple\nhandicap of mounting operating\ncosts, unregulated and subsidized\ncompetition and a steady lowering\nof the rate level, with increased ef-l\nficiency. Any thinking person must\nrealize that there is a limit to the\nextent that efficiency can be used to\noifset the effects of reduced income\nand increased outgo.\n\u201cAny thinking person must also\n(realize that the railroad industry\ncannot develop or even maintain the\nkind of service it wants to render,\nand to which the public is entitled,\n;unl(-ss the industry can, from time\n\u2018m time, attract new investments.\nAnd by the same token investors\n{cannot be expected to produce tlmt]\ncapital unless there seems to be x\nsome chance for them to receive a\nfair return.\u201d\nRelating this long term trend to\nimmediately improying traffic pros\npects, Mr, Baldwin contmued:\nIt isyparticularly unfortunate\nnow. when traffic is increasing due\nte improved business conditions, and\nwhen the railroads are commencing\u2018\n1 Lo spend heavily in improving their\nplants thus furthering prosperity,\nthat so many new railroad handi-!\n[caps should be receiving serious\nconsideration. And some of these\nproposals, notably- the train limit\nmeasure. \u2018can only serve to tie the\nhands of railroad manasement and\ncurb efficiency\u2014the one avenue by\nwhich there is any hope to escape\n;ihc tide of mounting operating\ncosts.\u201d\nThe president of one of@he prin-\ncipal Eastern railway systems, in\ncommenting on the effect of pre\nvalling low passenger rates on rev- f\nenues, said:\n\"No one knows and in the nature\n\u2018of things no one can know how\nmuch passenger travel has been in\ncreased beyond what it otherwise\nI would have been because of the re\nduction in fares.\u201d\n\u2014\u2014e\ni\ni WEEKLY W00 REPORT\nBOSTON. Sept. 10\u2014 (AP)\u2014The Com\nmercial bulletin will say tomorrow:\n\u201cThe market has gone almost flat\nthis week. Hardly any wool is being\nsold on_snmmer street of any descrip\ntion. Prices are easier in sympathy\n~with the decline in prices in Australia,\nespecially on fine wools, although it\nCis difficult to quote the market with\nSany sense of certainty.,\n\"Svdney is off 5 per cent on the best\nwools from the opening August 30 and\n10 to 15 per cent according to varving\nreports on the ordinary and inl\u2019nrim\"\nwaols of continental type. Japan still\nrefrains from buying,\n\"The piecegoods market i very slug\n#ish and specifications against old\ncontracts were withheld,\n\u201cNothing of moment is reported from\nthe West. Mobhair is slow and not\nquotably \u2018changed.\u201d\nThe Bulletin will publish the follow\ning quotations:\nDomestic:\nOhio and Pennsylvania fleeces: De\nlaine unwashed 40@41i\u00a2: 1% blood\n~combing 41@42\u00a2; blood combing 43\n@44c; 1% blood combing 42@ 43\u00a2,\nMichigan and New York fleeces: De\nlaine 37@38c\u00a2: 1% blood combing 40@\n41c: blood combing 43@ 44\u00a2,\nWisconsin, Missouri and average\nIndiana and New Fngland: 15 blood\ncombing 39@40c: 3% blood combing 42\n@4i3\u00a2: 14 blood combing 40@ 41c: com\n~mon and braid 37@38c\u00a2; black, burry,\nseedy cobts, 28 29,\nl Sconred basis:\nTexas: Fine 12 monthe selocted 95\n@96\u00a2: fine short 12 months 90@91a;\n\u2018\ufb01nn 8 months 876 88c; fall 846 85\u00a2,\nCalifornia: Northern SS@ 90\u00a2; mid\ndling county 87@SSc: southern 86@\n!FT(': fine scoured 8&5@ S87\u00a2; carbonized\nfine 8415 85\u00a2,\nOrezon: Fine and M. staple 944\n96e: fine and F. M. clothing 854 S7c.\nTerritory:\nMontana and similar: Fine staple\nchoice 97@98\u00a2; 12 blaod combing 95\n96c: 3% blood combing S5@S8Te; 14\nblood combing 80 82\u00a2.\nPulled: Delaine, $1.05@1.07: AA\n98c@$1.00: fine A supers 95@96c: A\nsupers 92@93c! L. B. supers (choice),\n89@90\u00a2; B supers (white) &7@88c: B\nsupers (stained), 854 S87\u00a2; C supers\n(average), 80@82\u00a2,\nMohair:\nDomestic. good regional bag, Texas\nspring 67@70c: Texas kid, 90@95\u00a2;\nArizona and New Mexico, 63@65\u00a2: Ore\ngon, 65@67c,\nDomestic graded: First combing, 62\n@65\u00a2: good carding, T5@77c: first kid,\n$1.15@1.20; second kid, $1.10@1.0\".\nCape winter firsts, nominal 354 37c;\nsummer firsts, 37@39\u00a2c; cape summer\nkids, 65@67\u00a2c: Turkey best, 40@ 42\u00a2.\n(Fereign prices in bond),\ne\n0 e\nBOSTON WOOT.\nBOSTON, Sept. 10\u2014 (AP-USDA)\nmestic wools received littie demand in\nthe market t\u00e9day. Current mill require\nments were small and not enough bids\nwere made to test the market.\nOccasional lots of fine western grown\nwools were offered at concessions from\nrecent asfing prices,\nLivestock\nSAN ANTONIO LIVESTOCK\n(Federal-State Market News Service\nEstimated receipts for the Friday\ntrade on the San Antonio livestock mar\nket consisted \u00abf 200 cattle and 500\ncalves, Trading was acuve uvn eariy\nrounds with prices steady with Thurs\nday's close. A good early clearance\nwas made on practically all offerings.\nSteers were scarce, Few plain steers\nsold at $5 to $6; short lots of yearlings\ncashed at $7.50 and down. Plain year\nlings brought $5 to $6.50, Medium to\ngood calves mostly $7,00 to $7.50, Plain\ncalves ranged down to $5, few culls to\n$4. Low cutter and cutter cows cashed\nmostly at $2.75 to $3.50; butcher cows\nsold up to $5 with fat kinds in light\nsupply with odd head to $6 and above.\nBulls were scarce, odd head of weighty\nkinds sold to $5; thin Kkinds down.\nStocker calves and yearlings were in\nlight supply, mostly $6.50 and down.\nHogs: Receipts 300 head. The mar\nket was active and steady to 25 cents\nhigher as compared with Thursday.\nShippers and packers were active on\ngood to choice 180 to 250-pound butch\ners, mostly at $10.25 the new top.\ni Best 160 to 180 pound offerings, $9 (o\u2018\n$9,50; 140 to 160 pounds, $8 to $9.\nPacking sows mostly steady at $7.50 to\n$8.25,\nNo sheep or goats were on offer\nFriday. N i\n\u2014_\u2014\u2014\nST. LOUIS LIVESTOCK\nEAST ST. LOUIS, 1l Sept. 10.\u2014\n(AP-USDA)\u2014Hogs: Receipts 3500; ac\ntive, 25@ 40\u00a2 higher; light lights and\nsows up least; top $12.05; bulk 170\nto 260 pounds $11.75@12,00; 270 to\n300 pounds $11.35@11,75; 140 to 160\npounds, $11.10@11,65; few $11.75; 100\nto 130 pounds $9.75010,90; few $11;\ngood sows $9.75@ 10.25,\nCattle: Receipts 2500; calves 1500;\nhardly enough on sale to make a mar\nket; mostly steady in clean-up trade:\nodd lots heifers and mixed yearlings\n$6@9: beef cows largely $5.00@6.50;\nculters $3.50@4.50; top sausage bulls\nquotable up to $6.50; top vealers\n$11.25: nominal range slaughter steers\n52.7?(@\u201817.15, slaughter heifers $5.50@\n15.50,\nSheep: Receipts 4000: steady: bulk\nlambz to packers $9.75@10.25; tn&) to\nshippers and small killers $10,50;\nthrowouts $647; slaughter ewes $4\ndown,\ne\nO S e\nCHICAGO LIVESTOCK\nNTTT A Ot T 0 T T AD ITOTYA L\nCHICAGO, sept, 1V \u2014(AF-USDA)\u2014\nHogs: Receipts, 5000; market fully 25\u00a2\nhigher than Thursday's average: top.\n$12.15. bulk good and choice 190-230-\npound, $11.8541210; comparable 240-\n290-pound, $11,60612,00; 150-180.\npounds, $11.25@12,10; most packing\nsows mostly, $10,0061050; few best\nlightweights up to $10.60,\nCattle: Receipts, 1000, calves, 500;\nslaughter classes fairly active, steady\nto strong; steer run mostly common\nand medium light weights and year\nlings, $7.75411.00; best yearlings,\n$13.50; part load 820-pound heifers,\nS13.35; grassers, $6.5079.00: all she\nstock more active and higher than\nweek ago:, strongweight cutter cows,\n$5.25. beef grades mostly $5.75@7.25;\nbulls steady: very few above $6.50 but\nstrongweight individuals up to $6.80;\nvealers steady, $12.00 down.\nSheep: Receipts, 11,000, spring lambs\nopening slow: bids and few sales\nsteady to lower: early sales good to\nchoice natives also 8 cars Washington\nrangers, $\u00a310.257 10.50; choice sorted\n\u2018natives held around $10,75: sheep\n~about steady, most native ewes, $2.50\n@3.75,\ne\nKANSAS CITY LIVESTOCK.\nKANSAS CITY, Sept. 10.\u2014(AP\nUSDA)\u2014Hogs: Receipts 500: market\nactive to all interests: mostly 25\u00a2 to\n35\u00a2 higher than Thursday\u2019s \u201caverage:\ntop $11.55: good to choice 170 to 260\npound 311,356 11.55: few 270 to 300-\npound $11.000 11,35,\nCattle: Receints $00; calves 400; no\nWeet steers or vgarlings of consequence\nL offered; she .\\'r\u2018k steady in mostly a\ncieun-up trade: vealers und calves little\nchunged: stockers and feeders steady:\nProspects of a fuir week-end clearance:\ncatter cows $3.504r4.50; few butcher\ncovs $4.756 6.50Q grass heifers down\nfroh $7.50: geod to choice vealers $87a\n110 few $10.50,\nSheep: Receipts 1000; native lambs\nstexdy to strong; odd Jots sheep\nsteady: few head native lombs $10;\nmest sales downward from \u00a39.75,\nMoney and Metals\nLONDON MONEY\nLONDON. Sept. 10\u2014 (AP)\u2014Money\nand discount rates unchanged,\n\nTy\nLONDON SILVER\ne e R R R\nLONDON, Sept. 10\u2014 (AP)\u2014Bar sil\nver steady and unchanged at 19 15-164d.\n(Sterling price equivalent to 44,35\ncents,)\n\nLONDON GOLD\nLONDON, Sept. 10.\u2014(AP) \u2014Bar gold\nadvanced 312d to 140s 7lad. (Sterling\nprice equivalent to $34.78,)\n\nT.ONDON COPPER\nLONDON, Sept. 10.\u2014(AP)\u2014Copper,\nstandard spot 55 pounds 13s 9d; fu\nture 55 pounds 15s; electrolytic 5%9\u201c\nbid 62 pounds; asked 63 pounds, in\nspot 264 pounds 10s: future 263\npounds 10s. Bids: Lead spot 21\npounds 17s 6d: future 21 pounds 1Ss\nad. Zine spot 22 pounds 17s 6d;\nfuture 23 pounds 25 6d.\n\nNEW YORK BAR SILVER\nNEW YORK, Sept. 10.-\u2014(AD)\u2014\nBar silver steady and\u00ae unchanged at\n447\ne\nNEW YORK MONEY\nNEW YORK, Sept. 10.\u2014(AP)\u2014Call\nmoney steady; 1 per cent all day:\nprime commercial paper \u20181 per cent:\ntime loans steady; 60-90 days 1%: 4-\n6 months 1'2 per cent: bankers accep\ntances unchanged; rediscount rate, New\nYork Reserve bank, 1'% per cent,\n\nNEW YORK METALS\nNEW YORK, Sept. 10.\u2014(AP)-\u2014Cop\npen steady: electrolytic spot and fu\nture 14\u00a2; export 13.85c. Tin firmer,\nspot and _mnearby 59.621zc: future\n59.1212\u00a2. Lead steady: New York spot\n6.50@ 6.55\u00a2; East St, Louis 6.35c. Zinc\nsteady, East St. Louis spot and future\n7.25\u00a2, Scheelite $30 nominal. Iron.\naluminum, antimony, quicksilver and\nplatinum unclmm.:(\u2018zl,\ne\nFOREIGN EXCHANGE f\nNEW YORK. Sept. 10 \u2014(AP)\u2014\nForeign exchange easy: Great Britain\nin dollars, others in cents. Great Bri\ntain, demand 4,94 11-16; cables,\n494 11-16: 60-day bills, 4.93 9-16,\nFrance, demand 3.55% cables. 3.5534,\nTtaly, demand 5.2612: cables, 5.2614,\nDemands: Belirium, 16.84: Germany,\nfree 4012 regisiered 2275, travel\n26.65: Holland, 55.02; Norway, 24.85;\nSweden, 25.49: Denmark, 22,071%: Fin\nland, 2.20; Switzerland, 22.97: Spain\nunanoted: Portugal, 4.50: Greece,\n911%: Poland, 1893; Czechoslovakia,\n3.49%; Jugoslavia, 2.33; Austria,\n18.88n: Hungary, 19.75: Rumania,\n.76: Argentine, 32.97n: Brazil. 8.80%n;\nTokio, 28.86; Shanghai. 30.00: Hong\nkong, 30.97; Mexico Citv, 27.85; Mon\ntreal in New York. 99.967% New York\nin Montreal. 100.0314,\ne\nObituary\nMrs. Laura Ann Churvi, 51. of\nTampico, Mexico, a former resident\nof San Antonio, died Wednesday\nin Muscatine, Funeral services at\n4 p. m, Saturday at the Riebe\nchapel, with the Eastern Star in\ncharge. Survivors. husband, Jack\nM. Churvi; son. Max A. Churvi:\nsister, Mrs. Lydian Sherman of\nAustin; brothers, George, William.\nJames and Joseph White of Pipe\ncreek,\nWANT ADS\u2014FANNIN 1231\n5.0 JAPSAND\n\u201cTHNESE STa\nRN\no\nJapanese and Chinese in San\n;lAntonlo haven't any hard feelings\ntoward each other even though\ntheir homelands are locked in bit\nter warfare.\nThis became apparent Friday aft\n|er a survey of the city\u2019s Oriental\npopulation.\nIn Houston, according to reports.\nthe two races are not only boy\ncotting each other, but also feeling\nis running high.\nNone of this bitter feeling is evi\ndent in San Antonio. The Japanesc\nare continuing to make purchases\nin Chinese stores, and the Chinese\nare being friendly.\nNOT THEIR DOING.\nSo far as the San Antonio Ori\nentals are concerned, the war in\nAsia was not their doing, and al\n\u2018though they intend to aid their re\nspective countries in funds and\nmoral support, they are not going\nto bring the war to the Alamo city.\nT. H. Wu, Chinese leader, said\nhis people here were united in giv\ning aid to China. Funds are being\nraised, he, said, through sale of but\n|tons, the proceeds going toward\nrefugees.\nA banquet to raise money for the\nsame purpose will be given Sep\ntember 14 at the International in\nstitute.\nFive Texas Chinese youths, he\nsaid, who have been taking aviation\ncourses, training as pilots for com\nmercial work in China, are ready\nat any time to leave for China to\ntake part in the war. They have\ninot completed their courses, Wu\nIsaid, and it is doubtful whether\nthey will be called.\nNATION-WIDE DRIVE.\ni Four of the youths are San An\ntonians. They are Wu Lung Tuck.\n!Wu Chi Yuy, Wu Chuck Foo and\n|Wong Shew Chuan. The other is\nfrom Tyler.\nWu said Chinese throughout the\nUnited States are participating in\n|fund drives. He said they had no\nhate for Japanese in America. Their\nlpurpose, he explained, was to pro\ntect their homeland.\nFrank Kuwamura, San Antonio\nJapanese, dispelled reports that San\nAntonio's 15 Japanese would boy-\nIcott the Chinese.\n\u201cIt is silly to do such things,\u201d\nhe said. \u201cWe Japanese and Chines2\nliving in the United States did not\nwant or bring about this war. We\n}want peace. Perhaps, like in all\nwars, it is the leaders in politics\n'who want war not the people\nthemselves.\n\u201cSince 1907 I have lived here, paid\ntaxes and raised a family. Some of\n\u201cm.\\' friends are Chinese. They are\nstill my friends. I continue to do\nbusiness with them. Why should we\nhate each other? We are Americans\n[now. We cannot help what the\n\u2018leaders in our homelands do.\u201d\ne e\n\u2018Funny Stuff\u2019 Under\nBan at Wedding\nS T T T T T S\nLOS ANGELES. Sept. 10.\u2014(#\u2014\nThere will be no *\u201cno funny stuff\u201d\nsaid Charles Corell\u2014Andy of radio\u2019s\nblackface team\u2014about his wedding\nwith Alyce Mercedes McLaughlin,\nstage dancer., tomorrow morning.\nHe made that plain today.\nThe wedding will take place at\nthe Wee Kirk o' the Heather. Amos\n(Freeman F. Gosden) wil] be an\nhonored witness when Superior\n_IJudge Frank Collier performs the\nceremony, o\n\u201dA\u2019\u201di\\rvr\u00e9v-aay honeymoon at Del\nMonte will follow the wedding\nbreakfast.\n122 Schools Built\nby WPA in Texas\nWPA workers in Texas have con\nstructed 122 school buildings in the\nstate, E. A. Baugh, state director of\noperations, reported Friday. Of\nthese., 14 were built at a cost of\n$206.611 in San Antonio, Baugh said.\nThe federal government spent\n$973.227 and local governmental\nagencies added $664.710 on the pro\ngram which will provide buildings\naccommodating 30,000 students. All\nbut 23 of the structures are ready\nfor use.\nDallas led in the numbers of\nbuildings, Baugh revealed, with 23\nconstructed.\nPresses Roll With\nConstitution Stamp\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 10.\u2014@#\u00ae)\u2014\nBureau of engraving presses rolled\noff today the first of 75,000,000 new\npostage stamps commemorating the\none hundred and fiftieth anniver\nsary of the signing of the constitu\ntion\nThe new issue, of the three-cent\nvariety, wiil be placed on sale first\nat Philadelphia September 17 and\nensewhere in the country a day\nlater. It reproduces J. B. Stearns\u2019\nfamous painting ot the signing of\nthe constitution.\nMoney Minus Strings\nWanted for Chinese\nMoney contributed for Red Cross\naid in China must not have any\nstrings attached.\nThis was the statement issued\nFriday by J. R. Locke, chairman of\nthe Bexar county chapter,\n\u201cOnly contributions which may\nbe used impartially and at the dis\ncretion of Red Cross officials will\nbe accented,\u201d Locke said.\nLocke said he had received word\nfrom Cary T. Grayson, national\nchairman of the Red Cross, that no\nworkers will be sent to China.\nEnjoy summer days more by driv\ning a better car. See Classifica\ntion 73, Light Want Ads, for a wide\nselection of good used cars: I\nDeath of Wit\nHalts Trial\nDeath Friday had savec Felix Fer\ndine, address listed as 811 1-2 South\nSmith street, from facing trial on\na charge of aggravated assault.\nFerdine was accused of assault\nupon Domingo Obregon with a knife\non January 10,\nWhen the case was called before\nJudge McCollum Burnett in Coun\nty-court-at-Law No. 1 it was re\nvealed that Obregor. had died re\ncently. Lacking a complaining wit\nness, the judge dismissed the case.\nStock Market\nNEW YORK. Sept. 10.\u2014(AP)\u2014Sell\ning forces fired a broadside at the\nstock market today with resultant cas\nualties of fractions to 4 points gen\nerally. There were a few much heav\nier sufferers.\nDealings were on the quiet side un\ntil around noon when offerings came\nout in volume. A little support ar\nrived near the fourth hour and the\npace again slowed.\nLeaders tilted forward at the open\ning, with signs of duplicating their\nrallying push of the day before. The\n\u2018move was short-lived and the down\nward drift soon gotunder way.\nAnalysts ascribed the reversal main\nly to what Wall street terms a \u2018\u2018sec\nondary reaction\u201d that usually follows\nsuch a slump as occurred Tuesday.\nThe news, marketwise, was no bet\nter nor worse than Thursday. While\nthere was less war talk heard in the\nboardrooms, it was realizegd explosives\nare still plentiful in the Mediterranean\n\u201cpiracy\u201d controversy and that inter\nnational dangers continue in the Far\nEastern conflict. Arguments over fall\ntrade prospects were loud and inde\ncisive.\nGrain and cotton futures dipped and\nbonds were uneven.\nShares of Allied Chemical dropped\nabout 10 points, Westinghouse 8. and\nJohns-Manville, Eastman Wodak,\nChrysler, U. S. Steel, Bethlehem Steel,\nDu Pont, J. I. Case, Lima Locomotive\nand American Locomotive lost 3 to 4\nor more each.\nOn the offside also were Republic,\nWheeling Steel. Crucible, Youggstown\nSheet and Tube. Geucral ~Motors,\nChrysler, Mack Truck., U. S. Rubber,\nGoodyear. Montgomery Ward, Deere.\nOliver Farm, American Telephone,\nConsolidated Edison, North American,\nAnaconda, Kennecott. American Smelt\ning, International Nickel, Celanese,\nParamount, Loew's, General Electric.\nSanta Fe, Southern Pacific, Chesapeake\nCorporation. Texas Corporation and\nStandard Oil of New Jersey.\nRersistant _were International Tele\nphone, St. Joseph Lead. Fajarado\nSuzar and Phillips Petroleum.\nAlthouzh steel stocks failed to re\nspond, some comfort was derived from\nU. S. Steel's announcement the cor\nporation\u2019s August shipments, while un\nder the July total, were the best for\nany August since 1939, Another de\ncline in the price of steel scrap was\nnot overlooked.\nA more than seasonal gain in freight\ncar loadings for last week served to\nbolster the rails a bit, although most\nwere inclined to trail the market,\nThe French franc again dropped to\na new low since 1926, emphasizing\nfresh financial troubles for the Re\npublie.\nInternational Telephone shares were\nenlivened by the company\u2019s 6-months\u2019\nstatement showing a net of 67 cents as\nagainst 26 cents in the same w:m\u2018\nmonths. It was note the report ex\ncluded undertermined losses of its\nSpanish subsidiary as it did in the\nprevious year.\nThose holding the business outlook\nis \u2018g rdly as bright as it could be_gave\nfuy cher study to the Montgomery Ward\nsales fizures for August which reveal\ned the increase over last yvear taperqd\nto 82 per cent from 18.7 per cent in\nJuly. Most of the gain was believed\nto have bheen due to higher pricea\nThe increase fro 7 months, however,\nwas more than 25 per cent.\nPoultry and Produce\nNEW YORK PRODUCE\nNEW YORK, Sept. 10.\u2014(AP)\u2014But\nter, 6635; creamery higher than extra,\n35@35%c; extra (92 score), 343c:\nfirst (88 to 91 score), 31% @34%4c;\nseconds (84 to 87 score), 2813 @31;\ncentralized (90 score), 333%ec.\nCheese, 24,942 firm: prices un\nchanged.\nEggs, 10,383, firmer. Mixed colors:\nspecial packs 2412@30c; standards,\n24c. frists, 22c; seconds, 20@21c; me\ndiums, 19@19%c: dirties No. 1, 19%c\u00a2;\naverage checks, 16@17c,\nWhites: Resale of premium marks\n3814 @39%c; nearby and midwestern\npremium marks, 35% @373%c; ex\nchange specials, 3014 @341l%\u00a2c. Browns:\nextra fancy, 33@38c; nearby and west\nern special packs, 27@32%ec. Duck\neggs, extra large fancy, 27@30c. Other\nwhite, brown and duck egg prices un\nchanged.\nY\n\u2014\u20141\u2014\nCHICAGO PRODVUCE\nCHICAGO, Sept. 10.\u2014(AP)\u2014Poul\ntry, live. 1 car, 69 trucks, steady: hens\nless than 4'%2 pounds, 19c: young col\nored ducks 4% pounds, up 16\u00a2: all\nother live poultry prices unchanged.\nButter. 10,237, firm: creamery-spe\ncials (93 score), 34 @34 %c. extra (92),\n331zc; extra firsts (90-91); 323, @33c;\nfirsts (88-89), 3034 @31%c; seconds,\n(84-87) 26@29\u00a2; standards (90 cen\ntralized carlots), 33c.\nEggs, 9553, firm: extra firsts local,\n21%%\u00a2, cars, 22\u00a2: fresh graded firsts\nlocal 20%c\u00a2; cars, 21%ec; current re\nceipts, 20\u00a2,\n\u2014_\u2014\n_\n_____CHICAGO POTATOES\nCHICAGO, Sept. 10 \u2014(AP-USDA)\u2014\nPotatoes: Receipts, 93; on track, 252:\ntotal U, S. shipments, 648; Cobblers\nbarely steady, slightly weaker ten\ndency, demand rather slow, best qual\nity russet Burbanks ard Bligs Tri\numphs firm, demand moderate; sup\nplies moderate: sacked per cwt.. Idaho\nrusset Burbanks, U. S. No. 1, few sales\n$1.60@2,10; U, S. No. 2, $1.30;: Wash\ninzton russet Burbanks, combination\ngrade, $1.70@1.90; Washington White\nRose, U. S. No. 1, $1.50@1.60,\nY\nT\nKANSAS CITY PRODUCE\nKANSAS CITY. Sept. 10,\u2014(ADP)\u2014\nEggs, 20c: hens 17@191c: springs\n1714 21\u00a2: roosters 104 12\u00a2: other pro\nduce and poultry unchanged,\no\nRebels Claim Loyal\nDefenses Smashed\nVICTORIA, B. C., Sept. 10\u2014(INS)\nSentenced to death because he \u201cdid\nunlawfully bite\u201d a small boy, a Bos\nton bull pup today had won a re\nprieve after a hearing in police\ncourt,\nThe dog\u2019s owner testified the boy;\nArthur Watson, had crawled under\na bearskin rug and reached out to\ngrab the dog, and the dog appar\nently mistook him for a bear.\n\u2014_\u2014\nSllQKESPEARE\u2019S CHILDREN.\nShakespeare was the father of\ntwins, Hamnet (not Hamlet) and\nJudith. He also had another daugh\nter, Susanna.\n\ne\nConsult Classifications 54 to 58,\nLight Want Ads, for schools, col\nleges and teachers.\nSEPTEMBER 10, 1937.\nUTILITY MAN\nGALE BREWED\ni T e\nAnother \u201ctempest in a teapot\u2122\nwas brewing Friday at the courte\nhouse.\nIt began Thursday with the rec\nommendation of the sheriff that\nJ. P. Needham be employed as util\nity man at $85 a month to replace\nH. C. Bigler, deceased.\nCommissioner Robert F. Uhr ob\njected, saying that no utility man\nwas needed, and the commissioners\u2019\ncourt withheld a decision pending\nUhr's conference with the sheriff.\nFriday, J. M. McDonald, business\nagent for the electrical workers\u2019\nunion, headed a delegation which\ncalled on Uhr to urge the employ\nment of a licensed electrician in\nstead of a utility man. He was ac=\ncompanied by W. B. Arnold, Amer\nican Federation of Labor organizer,\nand H. M. Haffner.\n\u2018When Uhr insisted no electrician\nwas needed, McDonald declared a\nman was needed to check the fans\nand elevators. Uhr replied anyone\ncould oil fans.\n\u201cDo you have to have a license to\noil a fan?\u201d\nWhen told that it was necessary,\nUhr replied he violated the law\nthen by- oiling fans every week at\nhis home.\nUhr said he was having the coun\nty auditor check maintenance costs\nand if it was cheaper to have re\npairs made by giving jobs outside,\nno utility man would be hire'd-\nDuke Used Roses\nto Woo Wallie\nDEYROIT, Sept. 10.\u2014(INS)\u2014The\nduke of Windsor courted his duch\ness with $350 worth of red roses\nweekly, Edward J. King said here\ntoday.\nKing saidg he should know. He is\nchairman of the London district of\nthe Florist's Telegraph delivery, in\nAmerica to attend a National Flor\nists\u2019 convention in Philadelphia.\n\u201cThe duke sent her $50 worth of\nJroses daily wherever she was,\u201d King\nisaid. \u201cAnd the redder their hue\n\u2018me better he liked them.\u00bb\nLONDON, Sept. 10.\u2014(INS)\u2014The\nduke and duchess of Windsor are\nexpected to meet the duke and\nduchess of Kent in Vienna toward\nthe end of the month, the London\nDaily Express reported today.\n\u2014_\u2014 e\nScreen Shot Costs\nMan Third Term\nLOS ANGELES, Sept. 10.\u2014(P)\u2014\nJeareld McDonald, 40, was headed\nfor his third term in prison today\nbecause his first wife, Mrs. Estille\nO'Neal, recognized him on the screen\nin a picture of prison life \u201cSan\nQuentin.\u201d\nMhen Mrs. O'Neal, who was mar\nried to McDonald in 1927 under the\nname of O'Neal, saw the movie, she\nbegan an investigation. She learned\nhe had married again, this time to\nMrs. Katherine Jensen, and notified\nauthorities.\nMcDonald pleaded guilty to a\nbigamy charge. He was sentenced to\na 12-year term in Folsom prison\nafter records showed he previously\nserve.\u00ae in prisons in New York and\nWashington.\nEmigrant A gent\nCharge Is Filed\nBexar county courts had \u201cone for\nthe books Friday.\nFor the first time in the annals\nof county history, a suit was filed\nThursday charging failure to obtain\nan emigrant agent\u2019s license, issued\nby the state for $1000.\nJohn Vrana, Jourdanton, was\ncharged with unlawfully transport\ning cotton pickers from Texas to\nMississippi in a case filed in Coun\nty Court-at-Law No. 1 by B. E.\nCavanaugh, a deputy labor commis=\nsioner,\nNorman Thomas Aids\nTar, Feather Victim\nDALLAS, Sept. 10.\u2014@)\u2014Norman\nThomas, Socialist leader, started a\nfund here last night to buy a new\nsound truck and other equipment\nfor Herbert Harris, Socialist worker,\nwho was tarred and feathered here\na month ago and his equipment\nwrecked. Harris, who was seized at\na park here where he was showing\nthe film, \u201cMillions of Us\", spoke\nbriefly at a meeting in city hall au\nditorium which was featured by\nThomas\u2019 address denouncing vio\nlence in Dallas labor disputes.\nFarmer Executed\nfor Wife Murder\nMONTGOMERY, Ala., Sept. 10.\u2014\n(\u00ae\u2014Arthur Oliver, 46-year-old El\nmore county farmer-millworker, was\nelectrocuted in Kilby prison early\ntoday for the ,muraer of his frail\nwife, Vidie.\n\u201cI have been guilty of sin, but\nI can say this crime was not coma\nmitted wittedly or intentionally.\u201d\nsaid Oliver in his last statement,\nHe pleaded insanity and drunken\nness before the court. The state\nchaiged he beat his 90-pound wife\nto death in a drunken rage in De=\ncember 1934,\nFoul Play Feared in\nTot\u2019s Disappearance\nOAK GROVE, Ark., Sept. 10.-\u2014\n(P)\u2014Fear of foul play spurred 600\nmen today in their search for 4-year=\nold Florence Jackson, red-haired tot\n\u2018who wandered off into dense wood\nlands of the Ozark hill country north\nof here Monday.\nThe child\u2019s father, Arthur Jack=~\nson, Chelsea, Okla., coal miner, sug=\ngested that she might have been\npicked up against her will by soma\npasserby.","height":"21288","width":"16596"}}
